{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488819"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:58:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"551"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/551"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.06,0.11,0.55,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43276"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/551"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"551"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28269"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3810"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6025"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34371"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43276"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a five-week history of right upper quadrant pain and lethargy. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and drinks two standard alcoholic drinks per day. On physical examination his pulse is 80/min, blood pressure 132/90mmHg, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. On abdominal examination some tenderness in the right upper quadrant was found, but the rest of the examination is unremarkable. A CT scan of the abdomen is performed and a representative slice is shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydatid cyst of the liver","Liver abscess","Hepatic haemangioma","Metastatic liver disease","Hepatocellular carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the right upper quadrant pain and lethargy in a 66 year old man, a potential diagnosis of malignancy should always be considered. The CT findings show multiple lesions of varying sizes, which is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic liver disease.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydatid cysts in the liver \u003C/strong\u003Eare a potential cause of the lesions seen in the liver, this is unlikely given the lack of source and CT findings. These parasites may be found in carnivores such as dogs or wolves. These cysts are typically spherical and well circumscribed with surrounding peripheral daughter cysts. They typically show calcification, which is also not shown in this CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given that the patient seems to be well and is afebrile. Patients with liver abscesses are generally unwell and have high fevers, and may have accompanying bacteraemia. The CT also does not show findings consistent with an abscess, which appears ill-defined and may have internal gas present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic haemangiomas\u003C/strong\u003E are benign lesions consisting of blood-filled cavities, often fed by the hepatic artery. They are typically asymptomatic and only detected incidentally, but can be symptomatic if particularly large in size. On CT, there may be flash filling enhancement - quick enhancement of the haemangioma during the arterial phase. There may also be peripheral nodular enhancement that gradually fills in.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatocellular carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E typically arises in the setting of liver cirrhosis, which may be due to a variety of causes (inherited, viral, lifestyle). These will typically show hypervascular enhancement patterns with washout on CT - not demonstrated in this case. The presence of multiple lesions does not rule out HCC due to the potential for multifocal HCC.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatic metastases may show multiple lesions distributed throughout the liver, rather than a singular localised lesion."],"references":["Pakala T, Molina M, Wu GY. Hepatic Echinococcal Cysts: A Review. J Clin Transl Hepatol. 2016 Mar 28;4(1):39-46. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27047771/","Gaillard, F., Murphy, A. Hepatic metastases. In: Reference article, Radiopaedia.org [online]. 2023. Available at: https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-6931","Bajenaru N, Balaban V, S\u0103vulescu F, Campeanu I, Patrascu T. Hepatic hemangioma. J Med Life. 2015;8:4-11. Available at: https://openurl.ebsco.com/EPDB%3Agcd%3A14%3A21276222/detailv2?sid=ebsco%3Aplink%3Ascholar\u0026id=ebsco%3Agcd%3A128831835\u0026crl=c"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28269"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"551"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15155"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15155"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c0d6368-0f03-4f01-8a4e-c85f4568628a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7c0d6368-0f03-4f01-8a4e-c85f4568628a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":589,"height":434}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28269"},"attributes":{"